383":"1383","1460":"1460","1350":"1350","6 February 1375":"6 February 1375","1382":"1382","1335":"1335","1411":"1411","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","1540":"1540","1505":"1505","Cossington, Somerset, England":"Cossington, Somerset, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Duntish, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Peche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: unexplained.","German: possibly a variant of   Pech   ‘pitch, tar’.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Peče</b> or of its Germanized form   Petsche  , which is also a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Pech","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Jose, Manuel, Alvaro, Diego, Edelmira, Emilio, Francisco, Gilberto, Jorge, Jose Angel.  German Gerhard, Hans, Ilse, Lutz, Manfred, Wolf.","Czech and Slovak; Sorbian (<b>Pěch</b> and <b>P'ech</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Petr</i> (Czech), <i>Pětš</i> (Lower Sorbian), and   Peter   (Slovak). This is also a Germanized form of the Upper Sorbian cognate <b>Pjech</b>.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>pech</i> (German <i>Pech</i>) ‘pitch, tar’, presumably a nickname for someone with exceptionally dark skin or hair, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who prepared, sold, or used pitch. This may in part also be the origin of a homonymic Polish, Czech, and Slovak surname (compare above and below)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret de Peche was born in 1355, in Warwickshire, England, her father, Sir William de Peche, was 4 and her mother, Eleanor de Canc, was 20. She married Sir Robert Latimer of Dorset in 1383, in Dorset, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1386, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1355–1386":"1355–1386","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1355–1443":"1355–1443","1384–1411":"1384–1411","1385–1460":"1385–1460","1386–1410":"1386–1410","1505–1540":"1505–1540","1352–1375":"1352–1375","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1460":"1460","1350":"1350","6 February 1375":"6. veebruar 1375","1382":"1382","1335":"1335","1411":"1411","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","1540